  <h1>CHEM 501 — Biochemistry (Fall 2025)</h1>

  <h2>Course Information</h2>
  <p>The chemistry of biological systems. 3 hours of lecture.</p>

  <h3>Lecture</h3>
  <p>Mon Wed Fri • 9:30p–10:20p • CHEM 108</p>

  <h3>Professor</h3>
  <p>Dr. Johnny Rodriguez (Dr. J)<br>
  Office: CHEM 465<br>
  Office Hours: Mon 2:30–3:30p; Wed 11:30a–12:30p<br>
  E-mail: rodrigjg@uwm.edu</p>

  <h3>Textbook</h3>
  <p><em>Fundamentals of Biochemistry</em> (Jakubowski and Flatt).<br>
  Link: <a href="https://bio.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Biochemistry/Fundamentals_of_Biochemistry_(Jakubowski_and_Flatt)">
  https://bio.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Biochemistry/Fundamentals_of_Biochemistry_(Jakubowski_and_Flatt)</a></p>

  <h2>Specifications Grading (Mastery-Based)</h2>
  <p>Canvas percentage is not the course grade. Grades are assigned based on content mastery using a pass/no-pass standard for Unit Exams. Passing = 80%.</p>

  <h3>Grade Groups</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>A:</strong> Pass (≥80%) on all five Unit Exams</li>
    <li><strong>B:</strong> Pass on four Unit Exams</li>
    <li><strong>C:</strong> Pass on three Unit Exams</li>
    <li><strong>D:</strong> Pass on two Unit Exams</li>
    <li><strong>F:</strong> Pass on fewer than two Unit Exams</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Plus/Minus:</strong> Determined by performance on the Final Exam (about 5% effect). The final only moves students within a grade group (e.g., A−/A/A+).</p>
  <p><strong>Retakes:</strong> Five in-class Exam Retake opportunities are provided. During a retake, students may re-take any prior Unit Exam to improve their standing.</p>

  <h2>Description of Course Components</h2>
  <h3>Unit Exams</h3>
  <p>Five in-person exams with multiple-choice and free-response items aligned to Unit Learning Objectives. Passing score is 80%.</p>

  <h3>Problem Sets</h3>
  <p>Ungraded practice posted on Canvas. Aligned to exam expectations. Additional practice is available at the end of textbook chapters.</p>

  <h3>Lecture</h3>
  <p>Student-centered and collaborative; attendance is beneficial but not required.</p>

  <h3>Final Exam</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Part 1: Cumulative multiple-choice (Units 1–5, 50 minutes) — used to assign plus/minus within the earned grade group.</li>
    <li>Part 2: If ≥3 Unit Exams passed, opportunity to re-take one Unit Exam. If &lt;3 passed, an in-person interview-based Unit Exam is provided.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Academic Integrity</h2>
  <p>We value a culture of honesty, transparency, and ethical conduct. Exams must reflect your own understanding; giving or receiving information during or after an exam is dishonest. In lecture and problem sets, collaborate actively and contribute ideas; copying work or relying on others without engagement is dishonest.</p>

  <h2>Support is Available</h2>
  <p>If you need accommodations or are struggling with readings, lectures, or assignments, please reach out to meet with me (in-person or virtual). UWM wellness and academic success resources: <a href="https://uwm.edu/mentalhealth/">https://uwm.edu/mentalhealth/</a> • If in immediate crisis, call 1-800-273-TALK (8255).</p>

  <h2>University Policies & GER</h2>
  <p>This course meets UWM General Education Requirements in the Natural Sciences. Students will be able to (a) understand/apply major concepts of a natural science discipline and (b) explain relationships between experiments, models, theories, and laws. Additional university policies: <a href="https://uwm.edu/secu/syllabus-links/">https://uwm.edu/secu/syllabus-links/</a></p>
  <p>UW Shared Learning Goal: Critical and Creative Thinking (inquiry, problem solving, quantitative and qualitative reasoning).</p>

  <h2>Course Absences</h2>
  <p>If you miss a Unit Exam or do not pass (≥80%), you may use the scheduled Exam Retake opportunities (five are built into the course). No additional retakes beyond these scheduled sessions.</p>

